<p>A post shared by Elizabeth Gillies (<?php echo e('@'); ?>lizgillz) on Sep 17, 2020 at 6:31am PDT</p>

<p>'Once we saw how dire the situation was, we knew we had to postpone,' she said. 'It was a no-brainer for us. Aside from the obvious travel and crowd restrictions, it didn't feel right to be celebrating in such a big way when there was so much going on in the world.</p>

<p>'It would have been in poor taste to burden people by asking them to risk their lives to come to our wedding. There were more important things to focus on. Our wedding could wait.'Â </p>

<p>'The virus really put things into perspective. That being said, we did want to get married as long as it could be done in a safe and intimate setting with a group that we trusted.'Â Â </p>

